has awoken my appetite.

37:11.417 --> 37:14.591
Time for a second stanza
of your mother's cream cake.

37:27.792 --> 37:29.669
I'll put the kettle on.

37:30.875 --> 37:32.877
Oh...!

37:34.000 --> 37:35.718
Phwah!

37:37.250 --> 37:38.968
Fuck!

37:40.042 --> 37:41.635
Another bath?

37:41.667 --> 37:43.214
My center of gravity has shifted

37:43.250 --> 37:45.878
since my last time
in a coxless pair.

37:45.917 --> 37:47.176
- You found David, then?
- Yes.

37:47.200 --> 37:48.918
And read some of his poetry.

37:49.000 --> 37:50.627
I've got some of it here,
in fact.

37:50.667 --> 37:53.216
He seems,
in his own graceful way,

37:53.250 --> 37:54.934
to have been recording
a wank in the woods.

37:54.958 --> 37:56.050
Well, any good?

37:56.083 --> 37:57.300
What, the poetry or the wank?

37:57.333 --> 37:58.551
Ted.

37:58.583 --> 38:00.401
- You know if he does it much?
- Oh, please.

38:00.425 --> 38:01.518
Look, my love,

38:01.550 --> 38:03.427
you asked me to keep
an eye on him and I have.

38:03.467 --> 38:05.135
And if wanking's
what he's doing...

38:05.167 --> 38:07.584
Certain things, a mother doesn't
need to know about in full.

38:07.608 --> 38:08.681
I understand,

38:08.717 --> 38:10.986
but I'm not being prurient
just for the pleasure of it.

38:11.125 --> 38:13.127
I've spent most of my life
skipping after women,

38:13.167 --> 38:14.794
like a puppy trying
to please his master.

38:14.833 --> 38:17.427
And the rest, pleasing myself.

38:17.458 --> 38:19.802
And that's fine.
I'm a heartier fellow for it.

38:19.833 --> 38:22.803
But if your son is writing
metaphysical art spunk

38:23.042 --> 38:24.464
and not simply filling
soft fabrics

38:24.500 --> 38:26.423
with human hand cream,

38:26.458 --> 38:28.131
then there is a problem.

38:28.167 --> 38:30.420
Which is?

38:30.458 --> 38:33.337
Mum, I think you should come to
the stables quickly.

38:33.375 --> 38:34.718
Lilac's sick.

38:35.000 --> 38:36.217
Oh, shit.

38:51.542 --> 38:54.625
Well, if the horse is sick,
he must do something.

38:54.667 --> 38:56.590
Yeah, well, I'm...
I'm sure he will.

38:56.625 --> 38:58.418
But first we have to find
the little fellow.

38:58.442 --> 38:59.915
Don't you have faith?

39:00.000 --> 39:03.425
Faith's great, but it'd be nice
to have a soupgon of proof.

39:11.375 --> 39:13.401
This is a rather drastic
course of action,

39:13.425 --> 39:14.497
don't you think?

39:14.542 --> 39:16.340
- She was fine yesterday.
- It's fast-acting.

39:16.375 --> 39:18.753
She'll have
complete renal failure.

39:19.000 --> 39:22.880
There's no ragwort in her field.

39:22.917 --> 39:24.839
Then do you have
another explanation for

39:24.875 --> 39:25.943
the blood in her stool?

39:26.075 --> 39:30.611
No, but it's not an explanation
for the blood in her spittle.

39:30.750 --> 39:32.127
<i>I'm sorry, Clara.</i>

39:32.167 --> 39:34.465
I think we're going to
have to put Lilac down.

39:34.500 --> 39:38.255
But I didn't even
get to ride her.

39:38.292 --> 39:40.044
Come on. Let's go
back to the house.

39:45.625 --> 39:49.129
I'm so sorry, Valerie.
This is just very bad timing.

39:49.167 --> 39:51.368
But there is a chance
that she will recover?

39:51.392 --> 39:54.796
It's a sadness, yes, but Anne
has a lot of experience.

39:54.833 --> 39:59.213
We need time for a miracle.

39:59.250 --> 40:01.252
'Hercule Poirot could
probably take a cursory

40:01.292 --> 40:02.313
glance at this group

40:02.400 --> 40:04.052
'and glean all sorts
of useful ammunition

40:04.092 --> 40:06.762
'for his denouements.

40:06.792 --> 40:08.760
'But if any of this amounts
to any sort of clue,

40:09.000 --> 40:11.753
'it's absolutely wasted on me.'

40:12.000 --> 40:13.627
I think you're being
very premature.

40:15.333 --> 40:17.335
- Oh, mon Dieu!
- David.

40:17.375 --> 40:20.504
Don't touch her. Don't.

40:20.542 --> 40:23.216
A sick horse
can be very dangerous.

40:23.250 --> 40:26.504
- Come on, come away.
- It's not right.

40:26.542 --> 40:29.295
- What happened?
- I'll explain in a moment.

40:29.333 --> 40:31.802
'What was happening was
the Logans discovering

40:31.833 --> 40:34.803
'they had no stomach for
mercy-killing a sickly horse

40:34.833 --> 40:37.803
'and yet were possessed of
a seemingly limitless capacity

40:38.042 --> 40:41.216
'for procrastination
and indecisiveness.'

40:41.250 --> 40:42.718
Maybe you should
come back tomorrow,

40:42.750 --> 40:44.252
and we'll reassess it and see...

40:44.292 --> 40:46.109
- Yes. Yes, my Lady.
- What she's like then.

40:46.133 --> 40:48.837
Thank you.

40:48.875 --> 40:51.879
Right. Perhaps some drinks
before dinner.

40:51.917 --> 40:54.591
Yes, perhaps several.

41:06.458 --> 41:07.909
I got the idea
from the playwright.

41:08.033 --> 41:09.810
Met him in Venice
on my last trip.

41:10.000 --> 41:11.297
Is there a point?

41:11.333 --> 41:13.709
Or are you merely recounting
a selection of random events?

41:13.733 --> 41:14.810
Ch, hush.

41:14.850 --> 41:17.424
Now, where was I? Oh, yes.

41:17.458 --> 41:20.837
Gianni had the most enormous...

41:20.875 --> 41:22.969
Oh, my God.

41:24.000 --> 41:26.344
C-o-c-k.

41:26.375 --> 41:29.709
And he was afraid
he might hurt me.

41:30.000 --> 41:31.798
"Gianni darling", I said.
"Fear not.

41:31.833 --> 41:33.801
"After what I've been through,"

41:34.042 --> 41:36.420
"you'll be lucky
if it touches the sides."

41:36.458 --> 41:38.711
"It'll be like pushing a paper
boat up the Grand Canal."

41:42.125 --> 41:44.218
This is not language
for when children are present.

41:44.242 --> 41:46.761
Oh, prude la-la. They know.

41:46.792 --> 41:48.544
There's two options.

41:48.583 --> 41:50.301
One, we let Oliver
rattle on home

41:50.333 --> 41:51.434
about his various exploits

41:51.475 --> 41:53.253
and the occasional ear
gets singed.

41:53.292 --> 41:54.839
Or, two,

41:55.083 --> 41:57.711
we let the kids work it out
entirely for themselves.

41:57.750 --> 42:01.755
I just don't understand every
person obsession with sex.

42:01.792 --> 42:03.743
It's not an obsession.
It's the meaning of life.

42:03.767 --> 42:06.170
Well, there is something that
children can learn with help,

42:06.208 --> 42:07.801
and that is good manners.

42:08.042 --> 42:09.809
- David, help with the plates.
- Yes, Mummy.

42:09.833 --> 42:11.176
Clara.

42:16.167 --> 42:17.510
Oh, mon Dieu.

42:17.542 --> 42:19.251
Will you tell us
a story, Oliver?

42:19.275 --> 42:21.503
Oh, I thought
you'd never ask, Michael.

42:21.542 --> 42:24.876
Well, the story is about
a down-on-his-luck gigolo

42:25.125 --> 42:28.709
who gets a job playing
alto sax on a cruise ship.

42:29.000 --> 42:30.840
- But what he's really doing...
- Oliver, stop.

42:32.708 --> 42:34.802
- Not a chance.
- Oh.

42:34.833 --> 42:37.131
Not a penny.

42:37.167 --> 42:42.549
Well, if we can't drink to my
play, let's drink to Lilac.

42:45.792 --> 42:49.171
May she have her miracle.

42:49.208 --> 42:51.802
- 'Yes, to Lilac.'
- To Lilac.

42:52.042 --> 42:54.018
'The same toast they'll be
making tomorrow night

42:54.042 --> 42:55.084
at the glue factory,

42:55.117 --> 42:57.591
'as her bones render noxiously
in the background.'

42:57.625 --> 42:58.625
To miracles.

43:03.208 --> 43:04.801
Unlike you to forsake a drink.

43:05.042 --> 43:06.840
You don't seriously
expect me to join you

43:06.875 --> 43:09.469
in a wine-soaked prayer
for a miracle?

43:09.500 --> 43:10.717
Is that so ridiculous?

43:10.750 --> 43:11.797
It's fluff.

43:12.042 --> 43:13.885
Miracles are phenomena

43:14.125 --> 43:15.793
that we're too frightened
or, in my case,

43:15.817 --> 43:17.419
too lazy to understand.

43:17.458 --> 43:21.668
But nothing miraculous
ever actually happens,

43:21.708 --> 43:24.177
and certainly no-one
is ever healed.

43:24.208 --> 43:26.256
You don't believe in healing?

43:26.292 --> 43:29.626
You can correct
a mechanical fault,

43:29.667 --> 43:34.673
but nothing can be truly
cured or made whole.

43:34.708 --> 43:37.791
Everything rots.

43:37.833 --> 43:41.417
And that's the beastly
bloody end of it.

43:41.458 --> 43:45.759
Would anyone like
a comforting chamomile?

43:45.792 --> 43:47.544
I think Tedward and I
might have a chat

43:47.583 --> 43:50.302
over something a bit stronger.

43:50.333 --> 43:53.177
'So, I was sent here
to investigate miracles

43:53.208 --> 43:56.712
'and have now been induced to
refute their very existence.

43:57.000 --> 43:58.752
'More than a coincidence,
I fancy.

43:59.000 --> 44:00.673
'Im beginning to feel
like doubting Thomas

44:00.708 --> 44:04.212
'on a certain easter morning.'

44:04.250 --> 44:06.844
What follows, you will never
discuss with anyone.

44:09.250 --> 44:13.426
My father came to this country
from Massachusetts in 1936.

44:13.458 --> 44:16.132
When the war came, he enlisted

44:16.167 --> 44:19.216
and trained as an engineering
officer in the R.A.F.

44:19.250 --> 44:23.300
Later that year, a young man
came round the base.

44:23.333 --> 44:28.715
His father had a metal splinter
in his foot. It was gangrenous.

44:28.750 --> 44:30.297
The boy knew the doctor
would amputate

44:30.333 --> 44:33.758
and he asked my father for help.

44:34.000 --> 44:36.344
My father touched the foot,
the splinter came out,

44:36.375 --> 44:37.501
and the wound healed.

44:37.542 --> 44:39.135
- Instantly?
- Yes.

44:39.167 --> 44:40.659
Well, I don't want
to spoil the story,

44:40.683 --> 44:42.551
but that could have
happened by chance.

44:42.583 --> 44:44.881
That was just the first time.

44:45.125 --> 44:48.709
A few more miracles,
and people began to talk.

44:49.000 --> 44:50.017
By the end of the war,

44:50.100 --> 44:51.768
he was being hounded.
It was intolerable.

44:51.792 --> 44:52.994
That was another time.

44:53.042 --> 44:55.886
It was 7O years ago, Ted,
not the Middle Ages.

44:57.625 --> 45:01.300
I never had a gift. L... l guess
it skipped a generation.

45:01.333 --> 45:04.132
It's a childhood fairy tale.

45:05.417 --> 45:08.500
Anne has asthma.

45:08.542 --> 45:10.751
Do you remember that hot summer
four or five years ago?

45:12.000 --> 45:13.826
'David and I
were out one afternoon

45:13.850 --> 45:15.423
'and she suffered
a terrible attack.'

45:17.583 --> 45:20.837
Mum?

45:20.875 --> 45:22.468
'Simon was there, doing C.P.R.

45:22.492 --> 45:23.558
like he'd been taught,

45:23.600 --> 45:24.673
'but it wasn't working.'

45:24.708 --> 45:27.302
Five, six, seven, eight, nine...

45:27.333 --> 45:29.506
We got back.
David heard the commotion...

45:34.292 --> 45:35.809
rushed in,
pushed his brother aside,

45:35.833 --> 45:37.543
and placed his hands
on his mother's chest,

45:37.567 --> 45:39.194
and she began to breathe.

45:40.417 --> 45:42.886
You're saying
David saved her life?

45:43.125 --> 45:46.629
Healed.
Not another attack since.

45:46.667 --> 45:48.590
'It's like Stephen Hawking

45:48.625 --> 45:51.834
'announcing he still
believes in Santa Claus.

45:52.083 --> 45:55.132
'I don't mind my old friends
turning into venal assholes,

45:55.167 --> 45:57.670
'but it's rather unnerving
when they go crazy.'

45:57.708 --> 45:59.710
Jane came to stay
with us at Easter.

46:01.292 --> 46:03.590
The leukemia had taken hold

46:03.625 --> 46:05.753
and the doctors had given her
three weeks to live.

46:06.000 --> 46:08.594
She wanted to spend them
somewhere peaceful.

46:08.625 --> 46:10.719
She took to her bed
the moment she arrived.

46:10.750 --> 46:13.503
The end of the first week,
she began to look better.

46:13.542 --> 46:15.886
'The second week,
she thought she'd get up.

46:16.125 --> 46:19.174
'The third week, entirely cured.

46:19.208 --> 46:22.257
'David had been with her
every day.'

46:22.292 --> 46:24.841
There just must be
a rational explanation.

46:25.083 --> 46:28.667
David's hands heal.
I've seen it with my own eyes.

46:28.708 --> 46:30.426
But I'm at a loss.

46:30.458 --> 46:32.225
We're private people.
We don't make a fuss.

46:32.258 --> 46:34.758
But this feels big, important.

46:34.792 --> 46:38.467
Do I hide it like a curse
or shout it from the rooftops?

46:38.500 --> 46:41.253
Why, in the name of
dysfunction, are you asking me?

46:41.292 --> 46:45.593
Yesterday, you made a big fuss
about being David's godfather.

46:45.625 --> 46:47.878
Earn the title.

47:09.875 --> 47:11.673
Hm.

47:38.083 --> 47:39.756
'There was an old poet
called Ted

47:40.000 --> 47:43.425
'who was in well over his head

47:43.458 --> 47:46.883
'he struggled to think
why he shouldn't just drink

47:46.917 --> 47:49.295
'and collapse assholed
into his bed.'

48:23.292 --> 48:25.966
Hello, Lilac.
I've brought you an apple.

48:51.125 --> 48:52.172
Oh...

48:53.750 --> 48:55.252
Go away.

48:56.250 --> 48:58.378
♪ Hallelujah!

48:58.417 --> 49:01.387
♪ Hallelujah! Hallelujah!

49:01.417 --> 49:03.715
- <i>I</i> Hallelujah! ♪
- Oh, what's got into you?

49:04.000 --> 49:07.129
Lilac is well.

49:07.167 --> 49:10.011
There are more things
in heaven and earth, Tedatio.

49:11.333 --> 49:13.131
You have heard?

49:13.167 --> 49:14.885
♪ Ai bien entendu,
ma vieille orange.

49:15.125 --> 49:17.628
Oh, by all means, come in.

49:17.667 --> 49:20.466
Why don't you ask Podmore too?

49:20.500 --> 49:23.959
If Lilac is cured, then maybe
Clara can be made beautiful.

49:26.583 --> 49:29.336
- Where are you off to now?
- To find David.

49:29.375 --> 49:31.218
Lilac didn't cure herself.

49:35.833 --> 49:38.712
Christ. Wait!

49:39.000 --> 49:41.423
'There is nothing to put me in
a foul mood more effectively

49:41.458 --> 49:43.711
'than seeing Oliver happy.

49:44.000 --> 49:45.760
'But the realization
that I had slept through

49:46.000 --> 49:47.843
'some kind of
miraculous occurrence

49:47.875 --> 49:50.754
'ran a close second.

49:50.792 --> 49:54.626
'David was yet to claim Lilac's
recovery as his handiwork,

49:54.667 --> 49:56.576
'but the notion hung in the air
above Swafford,

49:56.600 --> 49:59.444
'like a piss-filled Hindenburg.'

50:00.458 --> 50:01.835
I need to find your brother.

50:02.083 --> 50:03.576
I haven't seen him.
Er... but hop in.

50:03.600 --> 50:06.069
We'll cover more ground.

50:17.167 --> 50:19.215
What do you think
happened with Lilac?

50:19.250 --> 50:21.568
I always check her
field. There isn't any ragwort.

50:21.592 --> 50:22.840
Yes, I heard you with the vet.

50:22.875 --> 50:25.219
No ragwort, no cure,
no explanation.

50:25.250 --> 50:27.719
Saint David of Swafford
and his magic hands.

50:27.750 --> 50:29.343
Shit!

50:29.375 --> 50:31.753
Stop this fucking
motorized hairdryer!

50:43.000 --> 50:44.877
Mm.

50:51.792 --> 50:53.760
Oh.

50:57.542 --> 51:00.546
- Hi, David.
- Hello, Oliver.

51:00.583 --> 51:02.256
What about
this laying on of hands?

51:02.292 --> 51:03.464
Dunno.

51:03.500 --> 51:05.377
You're not in the miracle camp?

51:05.417 --> 51:07.260
Sorry.

51:11.250 --> 51:13.344
Have you ever seen him do it?

51:13.375 --> 51:14.627
Once on Mum.

51:14.667 --> 51:16.715
What happened?

51:16.750 --> 51:19.549
David put his hands on her
and she got better.

51:19.583 --> 51:22.792
No flashing lights?
Angelic chorus?

51:22.833 --> 51:25.256
She just came to.

51:25.292 --> 51:27.886
I need to see for myself.

51:28.125 --> 51:30.799
Fucking Jane and her "seeing
what needs to be seen".

51:32.250 --> 51:34.344
There we go.

51:39.583 --> 51:41.506
Where the hell have you been?

51:43.000 --> 51:45.879
'Pull yourself together, Ted.

51:45.917 --> 51:48.511
'Existential crises
are for wankers

51:48.542 --> 51:52.627
'and characters
in Scandinavian films.'

51:52.667 --> 51:54.284
I told you to look after David.

51:54.308 --> 51:56.382
He's nowhere to be found.

51:56.417 --> 51:58.843
That fucking horse has put the
cat among the fucking pigeons!

51:58.867 --> 52:00.294
It's my father all over again.

52:00.333 --> 52:02.802
It's in hand. You have my word.

52:02.833 --> 52:04.833
- Which is worth what, exactly?
- Well, it's all I.

52:06.042 --> 52:09.125
Oh, hello, boys.

52:09.167 --> 52:10.885
You're looking well.

52:11.792 --> 52:13.886
Mm... eugh! Eurgh!

52:13.917 --> 52:15.885
Fucking magic.

52:17.083 --> 52:19.211
Oh, forget him.

52:19.250 --> 52:21.878
He's too jaded to feel wonder.

52:22.125 --> 52:26.460
Whereas you... you have the
power to change the world.

52:37.000 --> 52:38.843
Clara's up next.

52:38.875 --> 52:40.422
I'll find him.

52:48.417 --> 52:51.216
'Oliver was gloating
over his own cure.

52:51.250 --> 52:53.594
'Now our fearless teenage leader

52:53.625 --> 52:56.253
'was sneaking off
to find Clara.'

52:57.792 --> 52:59.840
'If young saint David

52:59.875 --> 53:01.718
'could transform Valerie's
unlovely offspring

53:01.750 --> 53:05.505
'into some new-age Aphrodite,

53:05.542 --> 53:07.715
'that was a miracle
I had to see.'

53:08.000 --> 53:10.173
David? It's uncle Ted.

53:29.625 --> 53:31.168
'The steam whistle replaced

53:31.192 --> 53:32.443
by the turgid sound of diesel

53:32.483 --> 53:35.283
'and now electric trains.'

53:35.417 --> 53:37.795
- Mr. Wallace?
- I'm looking for David.

53:38.042 --> 53:41.421
Oh, one of the great
undertakings of our age.

53:48.583 --> 53:51.302
- What the hell was that?
- I hear nothing, sir.

53:51.333 --> 53:54.587
Don't tell me the last bastion
of sanity of this house

53:54.625 --> 53:58.300
is abandoning his faculties too?

53:58.333 --> 54:01.837
The greater the discretion,
the larger the tip.

54:09.083 --> 54:12.883
Do you know where David is?
Oh, come on, John.

54:12.917 --> 54:16.217
I know you see everything
that goes on round here.

54:16.250 --> 54:18.048
- He's a bugger for hiding.
- Go on.

54:20.875 --> 54:23.128
Frequently doesn't
sleep in his bed.

54:23.167 --> 54:25.626
Never leaves by the door when
there's the option of a window.

54:25.650 --> 54:30.632
In fact, he must spend most
nights out in the grounds.

54:30.667 --> 54:31.793
But where?

54:32.042 --> 54:33.885
'I licked the grass,

54:33.917 --> 54:35.669
'licked it clean.

54:35.708 --> 54:37.710
'Clean grass is hay,

54:37.750 --> 54:40.299
'gold hay for the flesh.

54:40.333 --> 54:42.381
'I hugged the leaves,

54:42.417 --> 54:44.260
'squeezed their green.

54:44.292 --> 54:45.635
'Squeezed sap is blood

54:45.667 --> 54:48.876
'and blood must be fresh.'

54:49.125 --> 54:52.675
And sowed the seed,
seed of my own.

54:52.708 --> 54:54.005
Oh! Hello, Valerie!

55:01.542 --> 55:03.590
Oh.

55:13.458 --> 55:15.301
Oh.

55:19.167 --> 55:21.841
Come on, Clara.
Just up at the woods.

55:22.083 --> 55:24.051
Oh, god.

55:35.917 --> 55:38.045
Oh. Ooh!

55:48.208 --> 55:50.336
Ow. Ah.

55:50.375 --> 55:51.467
Eurgh.

55:53.375 --> 55:56.094
If you let the spirit
in, it will heal you.

56:00.000 --> 56:03.379
Feel the spirit surging through
you. You must embrace it.

56:03.417 --> 56:05.636
Drain it, yes.

56:05.667 --> 56:08.170
That's right, drain it.

56:08.208 --> 56:09.755
- No! No, let her go!
- Yes. Fuck off!

56:09.792 --> 56:12.420
Aaah! Aaah!

56:12.458 --> 56:15.302
"Eursh!
